# Avoiding `useEffect` Infinite Loops

A frequent bug in this codebase: a `useEffect` fetches data, calls `setState`, the component re-renders, a dependency gets a new identity, the effect re-fires, fetches again — forever. The browser's network tab shows the same request firing in a tight loop and the page never settles.

## When this happens

- Any unstable object/function/array dependency in React effects.
- Any context provider whose value is `value={{ ... }}` (a fresh object literal each render). Most of ours are.
- Any object/function/array passed as a dependency that isn't memoized at the source.

## Rules

### 1. Ensure dependencies are stable at the source

Do not work around unstable context values in leaf pages when you can fix the provider source. `usePlatform()` should expose a stable `platform` object identity from the provider and read current state via refs internally.

```tsx
// BAD - unstable provider value recreates platform each render
export const PlatformProvider = ({ children }) => {
  const [state] = useReducer(reducer, initialState);
  const platform = { toJS: () => state.toJS() };
  return <PlatformContext.Provider value={{ platform }}>{children}</PlatformContext.Provider>;
};
```

```tsx
// GOOD - stable platform identity from provider source
export const PlatformProvider = ({ children }) => {
  const [state] = useReducer(reducer, initialState);
  const stateRef = useRef(state);
  stateRef.current = state;
  const platform = useMemo(() => ({ toJS: () => stateRef.current.toJS() }), []);
  const value = useMemo(() => ({ platform }), [platform, state]);
  return <PlatformContext.Provider value={value}>{children}</PlatformContext.Provider>;
};
```

```tsx
// GOOD - consumers can safely depend on stable platform
useEffect(() => {
  void loadStay();
}, [id, platform]);
```

### 2. Always include a cancellation guard

When a component unmounts mid-fetch (or the effect re-runs), don't call `setState` on stale results.

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  let cancelled = false;
  (async () => {
    const data = await fetchSomething(id);
    if (cancelled) return;
    setData(data);
  })();
  return () => { cancelled = true; };
}, [id]);
```

### 3. Trigger fetches from `router.isReady`, not from `router.query`

`router.query` is `{}` on first render in NextJS pages directory. Don't depend on `router.query` in the dep array — depend on `router.isReady` and read the param inside.

```tsx
// BAD - effect re-fires every time the query object changes identity
useEffect(() => { fetch(router.query.id); }, [router.query]);

// GOOD
useEffect(() => {
  if (!router.isReady) return;
  const id = typeof router.query.id === 'string' ? router.query.id : router.query.id?.[0];
  if (!id) return;
  void load(id);
}, [router.isReady, router.query.id]);
```

### 4. Memoize callbacks/objects you do need to depend on

If you must depend on a function or object, wrap it in `useCallback` / `useMemo` at the source.

```tsx
const reload = useCallback(() => fetchData(id), [id]);
useEffect(() => { reload(); }, [reload]);
```

### 5. Always check the network tab after writing a data-loading effect

Open DevTools → Network → filter to the request. Reload. If you see the same request fire more than once for the same id, you have a loop. Fix before shipping.

## Quick smell test

If your effect contains `setState` and a dependency has unstable identity across renders, you almost certainly have a loop. Stabilize the dependency at the provider/source with `useMemo`/`useCallback` (or ref-backed reads in provider internals).
